Using ArcGIS Pro's default transforms in model training¶

Import libaries¶

In [1]:
from arcgis.gis import GIS
from arcgis.learn import prepare_data, MaskRCNN

2025-02-13 16:57:48.685745: W tensorflow/compiler/tf2tensorrt/utils/py_utils.cc:38] TF-TRT Warning: Could not find TensorRT
In [2]:
gis = GIS("home")

Prepare for the transforms¶

In [3]:
from fastai.vision.transform import rotate, brightness, contrast, zoom, crop

These default values from ArcGIS Pro are mild. None of them drastically change the image. But they modify the image enough to where the buildings are easily recognizable. Data augmentation is a strategy to fight model overfitting, where the model memorizes the buildings it was trained on.

In [4]:
trainingTfms = [rotate(degrees=30, p=0.5), 
                brightness(change=[0.4, 0.6], p=1),
                contrast(scale=[0.75, 1.5], p=1), 
                zoom(scale=[1.0, 1.2], p=1),
                crop(size=224, row_pct=(0,1), col_pct=(0,1), p=1)]
validationTfms = [zoom(scale=[1.0, 1.2], p=1), crop(size=224, row_pct=(0,1), col_pct=(0,1), p=1)]
tfms = (trainingTfms, validationTfms)

Prepare the image chips for training¶

In [5]:
dataPath = r'/arcgis/home/Building Detection/DLTrainingSamples'
In [6]:
data = prepare_data(dataPath, batch_size=16, chip_size=112, class_mapping={'1': 'Building'}, transforms=tfms)
In [7]:
data.show_batch()

Train the MaskRCNN model¶

In [8]:
model = MaskRCNN(data, backbone='resnet50')
In [9]:
lr = model.lr_find()
lr.real
